Not true.  I'm talking about the search/index/tag/metadata paradigm.

Think about what problems SpotLight, Smart Folders and things like
Google Desktop are intended to solve.

These are one of the many ways we are seeing to flatten and query large
datasets.  As our personal data stores grow, the need for better ways to
retrieve the information we want becomes very important.

The notion is that you store the data you you want, in whatever
hierarchy you (or your DAM app) requires.  To retrieve some part of that
data is accomplished by having the computer do the hard work of pulling
that data out for you based on (static or dynamic) criteria, and
providing it in a view or format that is most appropriate.

I think it's worth remembering that the directory/folder paradigm came
out of a command-line interface designed for specific business computing
model decades ago.  While still worthy, it was never really ideal for
that use, and was always a bit of a kludge when adopted for home computers.

It has been polished since then, of course, but obviously there is room
for improvement.  Just look at all the different ways we have come up
with of solving the common problem of &quot;find specific data in this
hierarchy.&quot;

Apple, Microsoft, et al have had to respond, because as datasets
increase in size, this problem becomes harder and harder to solve, and
the user experience suffers as a result.
